members.comment: Used in some older DDS files for alpha channel only uncompressed data (dwRGBBitCount contains the alpha channel bitcount; dwABitMask contains valid data)
members.name: DDPF_ALPHA

members.comment: Texture contains compressed RGB data; dwFourCC contains valid data.
members.name: DDPF_FOURCC

members.comment: Texture contains uncompressed RGB data; dwRGBBitCount and the RGB masks (dwRBitMask, dwGBitMask, dwBBitMask) contain valid data.
members.name: DDPF_RGB

members.comment: Used in some older DDS files for YUV uncompressed data (dwRGBBitCount contains the YUV bit count; dwRBitMask contains the Y mask, dwGBitMask contains the U mask, dwBBitMask contains the V mask)
members.name: DDPF_YUV

members.comment: Used in some older DDS files for single channel color uncompressed data (dwRGBBitCount contains the luminance channel bit count; dwRBitMask contains the channel mask). Can be combined with DDPF_ALPHAPIXELS for a two channel DDS file.
members.name: DDPF_LUMINANCE
four_cc
members.comment: Four-character codes for specifying compressed or custom formats. Possible values include: DXT1, DXT2, DXT3, DXT4, or DXT5.

members.name: rgb_bit_count
members.comment: Number of bits in an RGB (possibly including alpha) format. Valid when dwFlags includes DDPF_RGB, DDPF_LUMINANCE, or DDPF_YUV.

members.name: r_bit_mask
members.comment: Red (or lumiannce or Y) mask for reading color data. For instance, given the A8R8G8B8 format, the red mask would be 0x00ff0000.

members.name: g_bit_mask
members.comment: Green (or U) mask for reading color data. For instance, given the A8R8G8B8 format, the green mask would be 0x0000ff00.

members.name: b_bit_mask
members.comment: Blue (or V) mask for reading color data. For instance, given the A8R8G8B8 format, the blue mask would be 0x000000ff.

members.name: a_bit_mask
members.comment: Alpha mask for reading alpha data. dwFlags must include DDPF_ALPHAPIXELS or DDPF_ALPHA. For instance, given the A8R8G8B8 format, the alpha mask would be 0xff000000.
Optional; must be used on any file that contains more than one surface (a mipmap, a cubic environment map, or mipmapped volume texture).

members.name: local_to_node
members.comment:
List of node indices for each triangle in the tile

			`local_to_node[triangle_local_index]` represents an index value to
			be used with nodes (see `nodes` for how to use it)

			All triangles (even non walkable) must be represented here.
			Triangle indices that are not used in this tile must have a `0xFF`
			value.

members.name: node_to_local
members.comment:
Node index to local triangle index

			Values must not be uint32_t.max

members.name: nodes
members.comment:
Node list This is used to determine which triangle a creature should go next to reach a destination triangle. `nodes[header.node_to_local_length * FromLTNIndex + DestLTNIndex] & 0b0111_1111` is an index in `node_to_local` array, containing the next triangle to go to in order to reach destination. `FromLTNIndex`, `DestLTNIndex` are values found inside the `local_to_node` array.
    $(LI `value & 0b0111_1111` is an index in `node_to_local` table) $(LI `value & 0b1000_0000` is > 0 if there is a clear line of sight between the two triangle. It's not clear what LOS is since two linked triangles on flat ground may not have LOS = 1 in game files.)
If FromLTNIndex == DestLTNIndex, the value must be set to 255. Note: does not contain any 127 = 0b0111_1111 values

Tile pathing information

		Notes:
		- "local" refers to the local triangle index. The aswm triangle index
		  can be retrieved by adding Tile.triangles_offset
		- Each triangle referenced here is only referenced once across all the
		  tiles of the ASWM

Translate triangle / edge / vertex indices stored in mesh data. Each argument is a table of the length of the existing list where:

members.name: this
members.comment:
Constructor for `JSONValue`. If `arg` is a `JSONValue`
 its value and type will be copied to the new `JSONValue`.
 Note that this is a shallow copy: if type is `JSONType.object`
 or `JSONType.array` then only the reference to the data will
 be copied.
 Otherwise, `arg` must be implicitly convertible to one of the
 following types: `typeof(null)`, `string`, `ulong`,
 `long`, `double`, an associative array `V[K]` for any `V`
 and `K` i.e. a JSON object, any array or `bool`. The type will
 be set accordingly.
Example:
$(DDOX_UNITTEST_HEADER __unittest_L600_C11)
---
JSONValue j = JSONValue( "a string" );
j = JSONValue(42);

j = JSONValue( [1, 2, 3] );
assert(j.type == JSONType.array);

j = JSONValue( ["language": "D"] );
assert(j.type == JSONType.object);


---
$(DDOX_UNITTEST_FOOTER __unittest_L600_C11)

members.name: opIndexAssign
members.comment:
Operator sets `value` for element of JSON object by `key`.

 If JSON value is null, then operator initializes it with object and then
 sets `value` for it.

 Throws: `JSONException` if `type` is not `JSONType.object`
 or `JSONType.null_`.
Example:
$(DDOX_UNITTEST_HEADER __unittest_L687_C11)
---
JSONValue j = JSONValue( ["language": "D"] );
j["language"].str = "Perl";
assert( j["language"].str == "Perl" );


---
$(DDOX_UNITTEST_FOOTER __unittest_L687_C11)

members.name: opBinaryRight
members.comment:
Support for the `in` operator.

 Tests wether a key can be found in an object.

 Returns:
      when found, the `const(JSONValue)*` that matches to the key,
      otherwise `null`.

 Throws: `JSONException` if the right hand side argument `JSONType`
 is not `object`.
Example:
$(DDOX_UNITTEST_HEADER __unittest_L762_C11)
---
JSONValue j = [ "language": "D", "author": "walter" ];
string a = ("author" in j).str;


---
$(DDOX_UNITTEST_FOOTER __unittest_L762_C11)
